title.narrative: Regional Health Integration to Enhance Services in South West Uganda (RHITES SW)

description.narrative: (Uganda): RHITES-SW supports 16 districts covering a population of approximately 4.6 million people. Although portions of the HIV portfolio will transition to local partners, RHITES-SW will support integrated quality maternal, newborn, and child health (MNCH), family planning (FP), tuberculosis (TB), nutrition, and water, hygiene, and sanitation (WASH) interventions in these districts. With $4,529,751 in FY 2020 health funds, four main areas will be prioritized: scaling up and strengthening implementation of high-impact, evidence-based interventions; strengthening community-level interventions to increase demand and uptake of health services; strengthening the health system to improve health services; and strengthening health information systems including data collection, completeness, and utilization. Major interventions will include: capacity-building focused on improving knowledge, skills, and competence; mentorship; promoting evidence-based decision making and using data to prioritize interventions; and strengthening supply chain management for effective use of commodities. .The activity will implement a quality improvement approach to address gaps in services delivery, undertake infrastructure improvements in MNCH services, and address the underlying behavioral, cultural, and environmental constraints to improve WASH. .To ensure continuation of services during the COVID-19 pandemic, RHITES-SW will align interventions with Ugandan Ministry of Health guidance. This will integrate infection prevention and control activities and support targeted provision of personal protective equipment for service providers and beneficiaries of MNCH, FP, TB, and nutrition services. .RHITES-SW will contribute to the Mission's Journey to Self-Reliance vision through meaningful engagements with all stakeholders and beneficiaries to identify, plan, and implement local solutions to health challenges, promoting commitment and capacity to provide quality health services..
